<h3>Starting Possesions</h3>

Every player start the game with the same amount of Poke or Keys.

<table align="center" border="2" style="text-align: center" cellpadding="5">
<tr><td></td><td><b>Jellicent</b></td><td><b>Klefki</b></td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Starting Possessions</b></td><td>1500 Poke</td><td>3 Keys</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Winning Conditions</h3>

In Jellicent, there are two winning conditions. Fulfill either one to win.

<table align="center" border="2" style="text-align: center" cellpadding="5">
<tr><td><b></b></td><td><b>Jellicent</b></td><td><b>Klefki</b></td></tr>
<tr><td rowspan="2"><b>Winning Conditions</b></td><td colspan="2">Be the last player remaining</td></tr>
<tr><td>Have 4000 Poke</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Rounds</h3>

In each round, players take turns to roll two 6-sided dices. Add up the two numbers rolled, and that's the amount of steps you will travel across the board.

<br>If a player rolled doubles, where both dice showed the same number, they get to roll dices again.
<br>If a player lands on a unowned property, they can choose to buy it or pass. 





<br><br>In the <a style="text-decoration:none; color: silver" href="https://play.pokemonshowdown.com/gamecorner">PS! Game Corner</a> chat room, there are two Tabletop games that share similarities with Monopoly. With 36 tiles on each of the two available boards, it may take a while to remember where exactly each property is located. 

<br><br>Worry not, there is an online resource that documents exactly that!

